# Project

You are building a Visual Studio Code extension called "SwarmForge VC".

It is a visual front-end for SwarmForge (Uncle Bob's tmux-based multi-agent
coordination tool). The extension lets a developer launch a SwarmForge swarm
against any target project, watch every agent work in live terminal tiles inside
VS Code, and get a pull request at the end. The developer never has to leave the
editor or touch raw tmux.

Important: this extension does NOT replace SwarmForge. It drives and observes an
unmodified, separately-installed SwarmForge. Think "a window onto what SwarmForge
already does", not "a reimplementation of it".

# Goals for this swarm run (Milestone 1 - the MVP)

Build the smallest version a developer would actually use daily. Deliver these,
and only these:

1. Target selection
   - A command to point the extension at a local target repo (a filesystem path).
   - An "Initialize Target" command that scaffolds and commits two plain-text
     files into the target repo: project.prompt and engineering.prompt (so they
     travel with the repo when the swarm clones it).

2. Tiled agent panel (the core UI)
   - A webview panel showing one live terminal tile per agent role.
   - Each tile tails the output of that role's tmux pane in real time.
   - Each tile is interactive: the developer can click into it and type directly
     to that agent, exactly like typing into the agent's terminal window.
   - The tile layout mirrors SwarmForge's window-per-role layout.

3. Run / Stop
   - A command to launch the swarm against the selected target (use whatever pack
     SwarmForge is configured with; do not implement pack selection logic yet).
   - A command to stop the swarm.

4. Pipeline awareness
   - Show which stage currently holds the work (read this from SwarmForge's state
     files under .swarmforge/). A simple status line is enough.

5. PR at the end
   - When the swarm finishes, open a pull request from the swarm's dev branch
     into the target's main branch. The human reviews and merges it in GitHub.

6. Named runs
   - Name the branch and PR after the work item. Keep a simple local log of runs.

# Explicitly OUT of scope (do NOT build these yet)

These are planned for later milestones. Do not start them now, even if they seem
useful - they would over-scope the MVP:

- No watchdog, heartbeat, or chase logic (rely on SwarmForge's own behavior and
  the human watching the tiles).
- No hardened message bus (read SwarmForge's existing state; do not redesign it).
- No completion-percentage "work tree", no backlog sync.
- No cost tracking or model/backend switching.
- No dynamic right-sizing of the pack (run whatever is configured).
- No per-tile respawn or model-switch controls.
- No remote access, phone app, or chat integration.
- No Windows support (macOS and Linux only - SwarmForge depends on tmux).

# Definition of done for this milestone

A developer can: select a target repo, run the swarm, watch all agents working in
live tiles inside VS Code, occasionally type a nudge to an agent, and end up with
a pull request to review - all without leaving the editor.

# Constraints

- Do not modify SwarmForge itself. Drive it from outside via its ./swarm wrapper,
  read its state under .swarmforge/, and attach to its tmux sessions/panes.
- The full product vision (later milestones) is documented in docs/ for reference.
  Build ONLY Milestone 1 described above. When in doubt, prefer the smaller scope.
